[[File:Southern right whale4.jpg|thumb|upright|"Sailing" by a [[southern right whale]].]] {{main|Cetacean surfacing behaviour}} '''Tail sailing''' refers to the action of [[whale]]s lifting their tales clear of the water for long periods of time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whalecoast.wordpress.com/marine-big-5/sailing-tail/|title=Sailing Tail|website=Whale Coast Route|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-11}}</ref> The process is rarely observed by humans, and the precise motivation for this phenomenon is unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/earth/wildlife/12191469/Rare-footage-released-of-humpback-whale-hanging-tail-in-air-near-Hawaii.html|title=Rare footage released of humpback whale hanging tail in air near Hawaii|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2016-03-11}}</ref> It is thought that whales either undertake this activity to catch the wind and 'sail' through the water, or as a method to cool down. A third theory suggests that the whale is feeding close to the sea floor.
Scientists believe that tail-sailing is fairly common amongst certain species, such as the [[Southern right whale]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2016/03/11/humpback-whale-tail-sails-as-she-watches-her-calf-off-maui-coast/21326396/|title=Humpback whale 'tail-sails' as she watches her calf off the Maui coast|last=Staff|first=AOL|website=AOL.com|access-date=2016-03-11}}</ref>
